title: My Little Joker Posed: Want Me to Die?

description.text:
I hate how all the models always just stand there. So mine doesn't. The Joker has always been suicidal, sometimes just for fun. And now he's pointing a gun at his head. "You want me to die, Bats?"

I didn't like any of the Jokers found here on thingiverse. Either they were Heath Ledger, or versions of the Joker that I didn't like, or there was something horribly wrong with the mesh that even IF you could fix it after hours and hours of work, the result would be dissatisfying. So I made my own. My goal was to create a Joker that did not only combine various versions of him, but would also be recognizable as the Joker without paint. I think I achieved that, as I sent an unpainted screenshot to my friend and he immediately said: "THE JOKER!"

The painting I've done isn't very great, it was just a quick paint job. Also, the screenshots do not 100% match with the actual model, as when I'm finished, I see something that doesn't satisfy me, and I change it. So the actual model is better than the screenshots. In my humble opinion that is.

description.text:
Project Name: Water Molecule Penny Test
Overview & Background: I am an intern at a Water Resources Institute assisting in the education and outreach program.
Objectives: To be able to not just show an image of a water molecule but let them hold and truly understand it. Through the activity we can also teach students about cohesion, adhesion, and surface tension and how they can affect water and your experiments.
Audiences: We do this with students from kindergarten to seniors in high school but the final info must be adjusted for age and learning goal.
Subjects: Earth Science, Chemistry
Skills Learned (Standards): Team work, properties of water, independence on working, and the properties of water Also a working knowledge of cohesion, adhesion, and surface tension.
Lesson/Activity: We use this in explaining the special qualities of water. We mainly focus on cohesion, adhesion, and surface tension and allowing them to design their own way to set up an experiment. They are told to figure out how many drops can fit on a penny. In groups of two they must do six trials three on heads and three on tails.
Duration: 10-30 minutes
Preparation: Explain to them the idea and give in groups of two a small beaker of water, two basic pipettes, six pennies, and a tray for the pennies to sit in. Have them predict which side can fit more (or if they might be the same) and how many drops might fit. Then let them go about figuring the rest on their own some will use on penny or all six, others will break up and have on doing heads and one doing tails. When they start make sure they keeping dropping drops until it spills over and that they stop when it does. Also that they do work together and exchange data. After they finish have them make a conclusion of which side held more (or if they found it to be the same). Discus their differing results and how that could have happened. Then introduce the idea of cohesion, adhesion, and surface tension, explain how this can affect the test they just did. If they are young talk about the difference in drop sizes or pennies. This is where you should use the water molecule and show them what causes water to be unique. Finally have them try to think of a way to take out as many variables as possible to make this test more precise and what else they could do to further the experiment.
Rubric & Assessment: Your going to want to make sure they made predictions, wrote down the data an a conclusion, but most of the credit should come from a lab report explaining how they did the test, how cohesion, adhesion, and surface tension may have effected their results, and how they could change the experiment or further the idea. If this is a younger group this could be done in discussion instead.

Here is the Magic Top Toy. There are severe things that make this toy and project unique. The top will spin for a long time; 1-2 minutes common, I have one time at 3 minutes! Domed glass surface keeps the top in a confined area. Once top settles into a perfect spin, it’s almost impossible to see it spinning; it looks frozen. You can hold the bezel in one hand (in your palm) and spin top with other hand, you can now manipulate the top on the concaved surface of the glass. And the Magic part(?) is you can print the attached PDF. Cut out the wheel with answers, place under dome/bezel. Ask your question and let the Magic Top point to the answer.

Uses a simple piece of domed glass (you can get at any craft store or clock supply online-“3.75 Diameter Domed Glass, only a few bucks).

Uses a printed bezel; print file attached. Bond glass into bezel using Silicone Adhesive.

Use attached PDF as a guide to make your own top.

Like to see ya beat my 3 minute time! LOL Enjoy, Reamo

Note: it takes any small lathe to make the top. I elected to make an Alum spin shaft and Brass Top Body. But, you are fee to create your top anyway you want. Weight is important and the center of gravity of the part is important, the higher the center of gravity the less stable it seems to be. The Top tip must be true and not damaged for best results.

Note: Do not use over hard floors (tile, slate, hard wood, et) any fall greater than a few inches will ruin the tip of this toy. Recommend over linoleum or carpet. If you spin and it goes off the dish; you are spinning too hard. Start softly and work your way up. Pay attention to technique and in no time you will be able to spin this toy with confidence.

Took inspiration from ebulldog's model. I actually got that one printed out, and my x4r-sb receiver didn't quite fit in there. The distance between the edge of the PCB that meets the antenna V-block and the antenna ports was too short, resulting in an insufficient bend radius on the wires. Furthermore, the positioning of the antennas on the x4r-sb are not symmetric, and I had to drill out one of the holes to get it to fit. I've resolved both of those issues on this model.

One thing which is lacking, which I don't know if it is a problem or not yet, is the lack of bracing underneath the antennas.

This is not your ordinary Starship!! A product of the late-80's, the Starship was a revolutionary design for the time, where composite materials were only used in small quantities, much less so on a civilian aircraft. Several things stand out with this bird aside the futuristic look. The canard system helps prevent stalls by pitching the nose down in high-AoA flight. The pusher design allows for a quieter ride save for a loss in efficiency, and the "tipsails" act in place of a conventional vertical stabilizer, which only "would have transmitted propeller noise into the airframe".

This was a very difficult model to create. As the aviation world prefers evolution over revolution, the Starship did not sell well, and with only a scarce few aircraft remaining in one piece, documentation and good-quality photos of the aircraft were difficult to find. This also marks my first attempt at designing the iconic Pratt and Whitney PT6 in a stand-alone nacelle. My models up to this point featuring PT6s have had the engine contained in the nose. Getting the geometry as close as I could get was very challenging. Overall I am satisfied with the work, but am eagerly waiting for you to print this so I may get feedback. description.text:
Another Whirilgig. This time it's Wile E Coyote chasing Roadrunner.

I had a lot of trouble with the legs. First, in figuring how they had to twist in order to become propellers and also not hit anything when they rotated. Then, how to do all that and still have both feet pointing in the proper physiological direction so they actually looked like both feet were facing front. After getting all that right, they needed so much support because of all the angles that my printer couldn't do a decent job of printing them. At best, they required a lot of cleanup after printing.

I finally just printed them flat and then put them in boiling water for a short time to soften and then bent them to shape. This works well, and the final product looks much better and works just as well, but it involves some mental gymnastics to figure out which direction to bend which part of the legs. ymmv. I used ABS for my prints, but this should also work for PLA. Please be careful if you use this method because, You know... boiling water!

I have included both versions of each set of legs.

There is an optional side b for the billboard. It is just a different ACME advertisement that you can glue to the back side of the billboard.

Pay close attention to which way the figures face in relation to the billboard when you get ready to glue the swivel mount to the base. The billboard should be on their right. If you get it wrong, the legs will spin backwards. Don't ask me how I know! :)

Assembly diagram is in the Assembly_guide.pdf file.

Whirligig in action: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OIgfxB2ZQw0

FlashForge Creator pro

Materials needed

2 608zz skateboard bearings
4 5/16" (or M8) nuts
1 length of 5/16 (or M8) threaded rod
2 6-32 (or M3) x 1" (25mm) machine screws
6 6-32 (or M3) nuts

Assemble the legs by putting a machine screw through one leg (be sure it is facing the right way). Then add and tighten a nut. Push this assembly through the body and add another nut. Do not tighten this nut. Leave enough space so that it can act as an axle for the legs. Add the second leg, again making sure it faces correctly. Then put on the third nut and tighten to trap second leg between two nuts while making sure the two legs can still turn freely.

For the swivel, press the two bearings into the recesses. Run two nuts onto the threaded rod, then slide the rod into the bearings. Add a nut on the top, and tighten to press the bearings flush. Adjust the nuts so the top one is flush with the top of the rod and the bottom ones are just snug against the bottom bearing. The swivel should rotate freely. Add a drop of super glue to lock the top nut in place. Tighten the two bottom nuts against each other with wrenches.

Glue all the pieces together and enjoy.

Designing along with Tips to Help the Slicing:

After a few failed prints due to bad slicing, I discovered the best way to get this made.
Start with the circle of whatever size you want.
Pull the circle up to a 1/2" height. If the program gives you a disc with two sides, then delete one side because you won't need it. The rest is done from the view of the inside of the disc (for perspective and working with it).
Arrange four deletable rectangles (1/2" mandatory by max length you want to make it) in a cross pattern that do NOT touch corners. (Touching causes slicing errors. "Deletable" because SketchUp tended to not separate the rects from the circle, so when I clicked to delete the rects, the who disc face vanished.)
Delete the Rects leaving 4 holes.
Still from inside, draw lines from the Rects's outer edges up (toward the open facing) to 1/2". The inner edges will have line lengths determined by the amount of slope you want. Mine is 1/2" rise over a 1 1/4" run. Physics formulas will help determining the best slope. I guessed. :-/
Connect all the lines on each Rect to complete the ball chambers.
Create a square in the center to accept the spindle. Push this square up for 1" from the face. Mine is 1/2" diagonal.
Draw a line from the center of the face to where the fulcrum of the top should be. Be generous. It can be corrected later.
From the fulcrum, draw a line from there to each vertex of the non-faced circle. If your program gives you perfect unsegmented circles, then draw as many equally spaced radii as you like. At least eight.
When done with the radii, grab the fulcrum and drag it so that it sits as close to the ramps as possible without having the ramps protrude. Mine is 1 1/4" from the faced circle.
Copy my spindle from the .SKP or .STL to use in yours. It was a beast to design. Suffice to say, by way of instructions, that the tapered edge on the circle is the same size (1/2" diagonal) as the hole in the Top. and the narrow end is 3/8" diagonal.

Optional Spin Technique with Twine:

Fold a length of twin in half and note the halfway point. Place it in the slot on top of the spindle. Wind the twine down the spindle. You might need someone to hold the twine in place on top and spin while you hold both ends of the twine relatively taut.
When ready, pull both ends of the twine equally while lifting slightly upward, The twine will release itself from the spindle and leave the Top spinning.

Project Name:

Power Top with Ball Bearings to Assist in Keeping Spin Power as Spin Decreases.

Overview & Background:

I was fascinated by the idea of how a skater's spin speed increases as they bring their arms in tighter to their body. Without going into a full lesson here, it roughly involves the torque forces and how they relate to the spinning.
This top can be design to have a greater slope that will force the balls to come in to the center sooner than the speed would allow or a lesser slope to not negate the torque forces as well as they could.

Objectives:

To learn how slope, speed, centripetal force, and torque are related.
To witness these forces in action.

Audiences:

Any one interested in physics and the math involved.
I'd have to say Grade 6+, with Ages 11+.

Subjects:

Math,
Physics,
Engineering.

Skills Learned (Standards):

Slopes,
Centripetal Force,
Torque Force,
Energy formulas.

Lesson/Activity:

Chalkboard along with any reference materials to aid in discussing the formulas needed to calculate the proper slope,
At least one computer and 3D-CAD software to design the proper Top,
A 3D Printer to create the Top when finalized,
Ball bearings to load into the top,
A flat level surface to spin the Top upon,
A length of twine to help spin the Top.

Duration:

About a week, depending on access to computers, and whether or not the design is done as a class, groups, or individuals.

Preparation:

Watch a video of an ice skater as they spin.
Discuss the science of how the arms are used to increase/decrease the spin speed.
Discuss the math of the science.
Use the math to design the parameters of the slope of the ramps in the Top.

References:

Any source of physics formulas.

Rubric & Assessment:

The final result of the project should produce a top that either increases speed from initial spinning speed, or spins significantly longer than it would have without the ball bearings.
Grading and Assessment could be based on how long the Tops spin. For fairness, the teacher should be the one to spin and time all the Tops with consideration for differences in strength of initial spinning power.

Handouts & Assets:

None.

title: Fan duct for ZoneStar P802Q with J-Head hotend

description.text:
I have a Zonestar P802Q, fitted with chinese J-Head hotend. I had problems printing PLA, after a few hours it jammed always.. No problems with ABS, though! But I figured PLA problem must be because of inadequate cooling, because the whole heat sink part was filled with melted PLA.

I found here one air duct made by widddo, but it was for the stock hotend. J-Head has slightly larger heat sink: 25mm diameter and 50mm length. Especially the length is a problem, the 40mm fan is mounted flush with the top of the heat sink, so lower 10mm of heat sink is not really cooled at all. And that is the hottest part that would benefit most from the cooling. This air duct has a guide to direct at least some air to the lower part as well.

This is not really a remix of widddo's work, as I did not use the original source code. But I did print his part before I realized it would not work. :) I used it as a reference for some measurements.

Installation:

Remove the cooling fan and the hotend fan. Hotend fan has M3 nuts, take them out and install to air duct. Lower nut is a bit difficult to install from inside of the part. Use M3 screw to initially tighten the nuts in place, so they will be at exactly correct position.

Remove the teflon tube screw, and clip the hotend heat sink to the air duct. Then loosely tighten the fan screws so the part is roughly in right position. Reinstall the teflon tube screw. It might be difficult because the hole might not align perfectly, that's why the fan screws must be loose at this point. Finally tighten the fan screws and reinstall cooling fan as well.

description.text:
This is a customizable ball bearing generator. The main purpose for me was to make a pair of ball bearings to hold a Hatchbox 1kg filament spool on a half inch rod. The second purpose was to practice OpenSCAD programming. The body of the code was borrowed from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:822960 but I wanted to achieve the look of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1570238. I think there are some weaknesses in thing:822960. For example, large flat surfaces make it hard to remove from raft. Also the center hub is a little weak. Thing:1570238 looks more robust but it doesn't offer OpenSCAD file so I generated my own.

Bearing height is the same as the bearing ball diameter. It is your responsibility to figure out how many balls to put in the bearing. Don't make the balls too small. It will be difficult to print well.

I printed my copy on a Micro 3D printer with white PLA. In general printing with raft and support help. It shouldn't take too much efforts to clean it up and it will turn nicely. Play with the tolerance number to make it work better for your need.

title: VW Golf / Passat / Polo  (3) GT & GTI Badge + Grill holder

description.text:
EDIT: because of this things recent popularity, i added an OEM scale GTI badge to the thing files, to save you the hassle of scaling it up. :)

--This is the mk4 and up OEM scale, if people need it, i will model the mk3 logo as well--

I lost my GTI Badge for my Volkswagen golf mk3 so instead of buying a new one i printed one, i used Loco's Volkswagen GTI Key-chain as my base and cut a few thing off. of course the size is not correct, this needs to be scaled to x1.4 for all the badges, this matches the OEM size of the original GTI badge.

The grill holder i designed myself, just use 2 normal wood screws to get it in place (no you do not have to destroy your bumper for this). alternatively you could use m4 or m5 bolts with lock nuts.

the grill-holder is the correct sizing no need to scale that.

i printed in PLA at 0.2 layer height and 30% infill, your mileage may vary.

The 2 components are printed separately, use clear kit or super glue to stick them together, works like charm for me.
